BHP Billiton Limited (NYSE:BHP) Stock Closed Much Higher Than Its 50 Day Moving Average 












































 Finance DailyDaily markets, commodities, personal finance and economic newsBHP Billiton Limited (NYSE:BHP) Stock Closed Much Higher Than Its 50 Day Moving Average
July 25, 2017 By Ted Blackburn Tweet
        Advertisement



Shares are trading at $38.89 a tad above the 50 day moving average which is $36.32 and marginally over the 200 day moving average of $37.26.  The 50 day moving average moved up $2.57 and the 200 day average moved up $1.63.  (NYSE:BHP) shares saw light trading volume with 242K shares changing hands in the last trading session.  Volume was down 93.58% under the stocks average daily volume. 
 These funds have also shifted positions in (BHP).   Stonebridge Capital Advisors LLC trimmed its investment by selling 980 shares a decrease of 2.9%. Stonebridge Capital Advisors LLC claims 32,471 shares with a value of $1,179,000. The value of the position overall is down by 1.5%. As of quarter end Proficio Capital Partners LLC had acquired  a total of 1,727 shares growing its holdings by 122.8%. The value of the total investment in BHP Billiton Limited went from $50,000 to $114,000 increasing 128.0% quarter over quarter.
 Fny Partners Fund Lp reduced its position by shedding 29,950 shares a decrease of 99.8% as of 03/31/2017. Fny Partners Fund Lp owns 50 shares worth $1,000. The total value of its holdings decreased 99.9%. As of the end of the quarter Morgan Stanley had sold 36,891 shares trimming its position 100.0%. The value of the investment in BHP decreased from $1,320,000 to $0 a change of $1,320,000 for the reporting period.
  On July 19 the stock rating was downgraded from “Buy” to “Neutral” by analysts at Citigroup. On July 5 the company was upgraded to “Outperform” from “” in an announcement from Bernstein.        Advertisement






 On December 7 the company was set at “Neutral” by Credit Suisse a cut from the previous “Outperform” rating. On December 5 the company was upgraded from “Sell” to “Buy” by Citigroup.
 Equity analyst HSBC began coverage of BHP giving it an initial rating of “Hold”. On October 12 the company was downgraded from “Buy” to “Sell” in a report issued by Citigroup.
 The company is now up by 0.26 percent from yesterday’s close.  BHP Billiton Limited announced a dividend that was paid on Tuesday the 28th of March 2017.  The dividend was $0.270 per share for the quarter which is $1.08 annualized.  This dividend amount was represent a yeild of $2.78.  The ex-dividend date was Wednesday the 8th of March 2017. 
 The P/E ratio is 41.73 and the market cap of the company is 103.49B. 
 BHP Billiton Limited, launched on August 13, 1885, is a global resources company. The Company is a producer of various commodities, including iron ore, metallurgical coal, copper and uranium. The Business’s segments include Petroleum, Copper, Iron Ore and Coal. The Petroleum segment is involved in the exploration, development and production of oil and gas. The Copper segment is involved in mining of copper, silver, lead, zinc, molybdenum, uranium and gold. The Iron Ore segment is involved in mining of iron ore. The Coal segment is involved in mining of metallurgical coal and thermal (energy) coal. The Company extracts and processes minerals, oil and gas from its production operations located primarily in Australia and the Americas. It manages product distribution through its global logistics chain, including freight and pipeline transportation. The Company sells its products through direct supply agreements with its customers and on global commodity exchanges. Its businesses include Minerals Australia, Minerals Americas, Petroleum and Marketing..
